## Create users rj and cj in devops group (python - AWS Ubuntu EC2 on Server 1 and Server 2)
## 📌 Overview
Step 1: Install venv
sudo apt update
sudo apt install python3-venv -y
Step 2: Create virtual environment
python3 -m venv myenv
Step 3: Activate it
source myenv/bin/activate
Step 4: Install Paramiko
pip install paramiko
Step 5: Create Python Script
nano setup_users.py
import paramiko
KEY_FILE = "key.pem"
USER = "ubuntu"
SERVERS = [
    "54.80.245.87",
    "100.31.57.106"
]
COMMANDS = [
    "sudo groupadd devops 2>/dev/null || true",
    "sudo useradd -m rj 2>/dev/null || true",
    "sudo useradd -m cj 2>/dev/null || true",
    "sudo usermod -aG devops rj",
    "sudo usermod -aG devops cj",
    "id rj",
    "id cj"
]
def run_commands(ip):
    print(f"Connecting to {ip}...")

    key = paramiko.RSAKey.from_private_key_file(KEY_FILE)

    ssh = paramiko.SSHClient()
    ssh.set_missing_host_key_policy(paramiko.AutoAddPolicy())

    try:
        ssh.connect(hostname=ip, username=USER, pkey=key)

        for cmd in COMMANDS:
            stdin, stdout, stderr = ssh.exec_command(cmd)
            print(stdout.read().decode())

        print(f"Done on {ip}")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Failed on {ip}: {e}")

    finally:
        ssh.close()

for server in SERVERS:
    run_commands(server)
Step 6: Run Script
python setup_users.py

🚀 Ansible Setup: Create Users on EC2 (Server 1 & 2)
🧭 Architecture
Local Machine (Server 3) → Ansible control node
Server 1 & 2 (EC2 Ubuntu) → managed nodes
Step 1: Install Ansible (Local Machine)
Ubuntu / WSL / Linux:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install ansible -y
Mac:
brew install ansible
Verify:
ansible --version
Step 2: Prepare SSH Key
chmod 400 key.pem
Step 3: Create Inventory File
nano inventory.ini
[servers]
54.80.245.87
100.31.57.106
[servers:vars]
ansible_user=ubuntu
ansible_ssh_private_key_file=key.pem
Step 4: Test Connection
ansible all -i inventory.ini -m ping
Expected:
SUCCESS
👉 If this fails → fix SSH first
Step 5: Create Playbook
nano setup-users.yml
📜 Ansible Playbook
---
name: Create users and group on EC2
  hosts: servers
  become: yes
  tasks:
    - name: Create devops group
      group:
        name: devops
        state: present

    - name: Create user rj
      user:
        name: rj
        state: present
        groups: devops
        append: yes

    - name: Create user cj
      user:
        name: cj
        state: present
        groups: devops
        append: yes

    - name: Verify rj
      command: id rj
      register: rj_output

    - debug:
        var: rj_output.stdout

    - name: Verify cj
      command: id cj
      register: cj_output

    - debug:
        var: cj_output.stdout
Step 6: Run Playbook
ansible-playbook -i inventory.ini setup-users.yml


Ansible is better because it automates tasks across many servers in a simple, repeatable, and error-free way without needing custom scripts or extra setup on the servers.


